Reference-contexts: For the system to run a user's job, the user must supply the system with enough "money" to cover the cost of running the job. "Money" in this context refers to an electronic currency represented as coins <ref> [1] </ref>. Coins are available in various denominations, and are represented as an encrypted serial number. Coins are issued by a system-wide bank, which keeps track of the serial numbers that have been issued. <p> All verification transactions between servers and the bank are encrypted, and a multiple-key public-key protocol is used to verify the validity of coins <ref> [1] </ref>. Thus, the bank's public keys must initially be distributed to all members of the system. <p> (t; Cost (t) in the simplest case (assuming a piecewise linear cost function between those points), or, in an expanded version of the system, it could be a representation of a continuous mathematical function. 4.1.4 Coins Coins in this system are represented as described in the DigiCash electronic money system <ref> [1] </ref>. Essentially, a coin is a bank-issued serial number that has been digitally signed by the bank's private key. The bank has a number of private keys, each one representing one possible denomination for a coin.
